<font color="#FF0000">WHAT CAN WE DO?</font><br>
<tt>Mon Nov 10 17:07:33 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Homeless Vietnam Veterans, what can we do?<br><br>
I read the story above this morning from the wires of the Associate Press.  While the figure may be disputed in regards to the total Vietnam veterans that are homeless, I believe the full story has not been accurately reported. I spoke to Phil  Rydman, spokesman for the International Union of Gospel Missions, in Kansas City this morning and asked him how the survey was conducted. <br><br>
He said that a person seeking shelter for the night would simply be asked to answer their inquiry, as they entered their shelters. No forms were filled out and there was no means made for verification. He did say that they felt comfortable with their survey as they somewhat verified the individuals answer according to that persons age appearance. A heck of a way to verify an individuals veteran status. He further mentioned that the person was not given any preferential treatment so there would be no reason for them to lie. <br><br>
He was, as I was, surprised by the number of Golf War veterans showing up at the homeless shelters and could not understand why, other then what he has said in the press release. I feel uncomfortable with these figures as they are not verifiable or very reliable, but I know they will be used by many up in the years ahead to substantiate what a burden the Vietnam Veteran continues to be to society.  <br><br>
The question we need to ask is, Why would a mission release this type of information? <br>
For added financial aid may very well be a good reason, much like the homeless person on the freeway off ramp would find it advantageous to write “Homeless Veteran,” on his cardboard sign in hopes of obtaining greater financial sympathy form the motorist public. But how many of those freeway solicitors are actual Vietnam Veterans? I have yet to find a Vietnam Veteran carrying such a sign where I live. I don’t doubt that there are Vietnam Veterans that are homeless and like anyone else could be found asking for funds at freeway offramps, its just that those I have questioned have turned out NOT to be Vietnam veterans. Neither do those individuals want to work for food as many of their signs proclaim. <br><br>
The Veterans Administration figures show about 19 percent of the male population are former members of the armed forces. Overall according to Rydman over 60% of the homeless men in America are veterans, 10% from  Korean and another 10% from the Gulf War.<br><br>
While I support giving an individual needing a helping hand a break or assistance, the stigma attached to 41% being Vietnam Veterans as stated in the Associated Press news story above, is discomforting. <br><br>
If it is correct we have failed miserably to meet the most common need of the warrior soldier that fought our country’s battle.  Including the additional 20% identified as being homeless military servicemen that served in the Korean and Gulf Wars. Still something seems to be very wrong with these figures. <br><br>
News reporters will now use this new information, especially since it was reported by the Associated Press as gospel truth, no punt intended with the fact that it was a Union of Gospel Missions, spokesmen that released the story.  It will be accepted while no real verification occurred. None the less this information or disinformation will be added to historical folders of our educational institutions as facts associated with the Vietnam veteran. <br><br>
The problem I see is, what if the figures are true? Or, what if by disputing those findings the Union Gospel Mission or other homeless shelters suffer financial lost and because of this the needs of veterans are not met?<br>
It’s a heck of a catch 22 we find ourselves in, but then again we as Vietnam Veterans are used to it. So why not suffer some more. Accept it and it brings us shame, deny it and it brings us shame, for to provide not for our own, is unacceptable for the war veteran.<br>
But, now what can we do?<br><br>
I’m Cook Barela and those are my thoughts. <br>

